document.title: Archdiocese of Milwaukee Curriculum Documents for Educators (Exit Expectations)

1125706132E24D7BAE14928D33237B7E.description:
Work collaboratively and respect the ideas,
roles, and abilities of others.

84A91DD4E1C5409181FBA2BEB417774D.description:
Identify the relationships between the roles of
science, technology, and Catholic ethics in the
global community.

C14FFA468CB34B7C996805BC891F2DF6.description:
Appreciate that many different people of
varied cultures have made contributions that
benefit both science and society

C6B1152DFBC74A19B02667FE64C80BD4.description:
Communicate how the data generated by the
model can be used to optimize the design
solution through iterative testing and
modification.

56B2C0B69EA74CA186A004B9524B041C.description:
The iterative process of testing the most
promising solutions and modifying what is
proposed on the basis of the test results leads
to greater refinement and ultimately to an
optimal solution.

C501D752CD574EC8BFA2C200A9583729.description:
Models of all kinds are important for testing
solutions.

35A576BEE0CE4A35B94BB445CA6C8B64.description:
A solution needs to be tested, and then
modified on the basis of the test results, in
order to improve it.

662656417C3E4C9CA247073EF585AF3A.description:
Develop a model to generate data
for iterative testing and modification of a
proposed object, tool, or process such that an
optimal design can be achieved.

29978BB292A14E37A6CF1075503E5E91.description:
Evaluate the design that best meets the given
criteria and constraints.

20B7DB0D28D24650A6FBD67B91C82B8B.description:
Analyze the data and identify relationships
within the datasets, including relationships
between the design solutions and the given
criteria and constraints.

B8BF59CDCBD3421C843C5C394E65F9BB.description:
Organize given data (e.g., via tables, charts, or
graphs) from tests intended to determine the
effectiveness of the solution

5DF37B42E8FC48E89EF846E808099E2A.description:
Although one design may not perform the best
across all tests, identifying the characteristics
of the design that performed the best in each
test can provide useful information for the
redesign process—that is, some of those
characteristics may be incorporated into the
new design.

E6B23200E88C4CBF88827275E87277C4.description:
Sometimes parts of different solutions can be
combined to create a solution that is better
than any of its predecessors

1FDCDC1D22284903B981E801CE432F8D.description:
There are systematic processes for evaluating
solutions with respect to how well they meet
the criteria and constraints of a problem.

DC9B2FFE1FFA49EBB2243A9FBE06D29D.description:
Analyze data from tests to
determine similarities and differences among
several design solutions to identify the best
characteristics of each that can be combined into
a new solution to better meet the criteria for
success.

D153558CB3454657A6B9EB05A1869778.description:
Develop and apply a systematic method (e.g.,
a decision matrix) to identify the strengths and
weaknesses of each solution.

FB891B6F8651443FA5017684CD3AF24A.description:
There are systematic processes for evaluating
solutions with respect to how well they meet
the criteria and constraints of a problem.

9D5EF1F912D043B2AFFE0CDA1D9A7257.description:
Evaluate competing design solutions
using a systematic process to determine how
well they meet the criteria and constraints of the
problem.

AE8E2FDA15D24A86927672D05D62AAB9.description:
Define criteria and constraints that must be
taken into account in the solution.

461BF2605D304FBFB97C6C206F5F3829.description:
Describe a problem that can be solved through
the development of an object, tool, process, or
system.

3C040F78055941B98FD89226BFDA3107.description:
Specification of constraints includes
consideration of scientific principles and other
relevant knowledge that are likely to limit
possible solutions.

C3DD3412EE8343C79533F6038CEF788C.description:
The more precisely a design task’s criteria and
constraints can be defined, the more likely it is
that the designed solution will be successful.

8048A6515B6B4E83BDDC3206F0664F4D.description:
Define and delimit the criteria and
constraints of a design problem with sufficient
precision to ensure a successful solution, taking
into account relevant scientific principles and
potential impacts on people and the natural
environment that may limit possible solutions.

636038C0ECFD437BAAFE08A3DB4B9982.description:
Work collaboratively and respect the ideas,
roles, and abilities of others.

EDA9C3F025864C0F93261221D9D58287.description:
Identify the relationships between the roles of
science, technology, and Catholic ethics in the
global community. (ES.3.2)

D3B7016F16BA4753A8BDB1D6DE4E493A.description:
Demonstrate stewardship inspired by Catholic
values in the care of local and global
environments. (ES.3.3)

889065BB6B6747E4AB34479736EC938F.description:
Analyze tables, graphs, or maps of global
regional temperatures and atmospheric levels
of gases (such as carbon dioxide and methane)
to generate questions and possible solutions to
reduce the impact of global climate change.

F1F9F68514904CA0B8F179B089AF5B1F.description:
Investigate how the greenhouse effect leads to
global climate change.

F49C9E617F0D44C6A028C0B520B4B482.description:
Reducing the level of climate change and
reducing human vulnerability to whatever climate
changes do occur depend on the understanding
of climate science, engineering capabilities, and
other kinds of knowledge, such as understanding
of human behavior and on applying that
knowledge wisely in decisions and activities.

91A827C88904428CB8827A76091AC90F.description:
Human activities are major factors in the current
rise in Earth’s mean surface temperature (global
warming).

9426893197F0469983B9372AD17B3C3E.description:
Ask questions to clarify evidence
of the factors that have caused the rise in
global temperatures over the past century.

C978181C5BA54173B52989D1D74654C6.description:
Outline the arguments using evidence to
illustrate the human impact on natural
resources.

1573EA16B63341BDB54A20FC95D8E888.description:
Identify one natural resource that is impacted
by an increase in human population.

CC2EF2303BF84DC3A8E51C487455426E.description:
Examples of natural resources could include, but
are not limited to water quality, air quality, land
use, soil, glaciers, fossil fuels, minerals, ocean
resources.

197E4264071341848BCDE782092D312E.description:
Typically as human populations and per-capita
consumption of natural resources increase, so do
the negative impacts on Earth unless the activities
and technologies involved are engineered
otherwise.

022CF9FD8C874688A58990DF14F55216.description:
Construct an argument supported
by evidence for how increases in human
population and per-capita consumption of
natural resources impact Earth’s systems.

646211B07C7B493CA1088C1A2159642F.description:
Develop/Design a solution to a local
environmental issue (urban development,
agriculture, wetland removal, pollution,
withdrawal of water from streams and aquifer).

788AAF45A544430AA1F26E046B82DFDE.description:
Evaluate the impact of global
development/expansion (on earth structures).

357B7D69D91D4E12B6A7E396B581A8E1.description:
Compare and contrast the effects of
environmental changes on living things.

B38583B1BB2847B78240A3211C676BA9.description:
Changes to Earth’s environments can have
different impacts (negative and positive) for
different living things.

3CE72C2F20FB48E39A662AB4C2396B06.description:
Human activities have significantly altered the
biosphere, sometimes damaging or destroying
natural habitats and causing the extinction of
other species.

DB9405C38DDB4E4C9A3047C3768F029C.description:
Apply scientific principles to
design a method for monitoring and
minimizing a human impact on the
environment.

86B8AC4E05AC4ADEBB22ED4BF9946BCC.description:
Describe technologies used to predict, monitor
and minimize the effects of natural hazards.

469F5229222543078898D36C4D78F770.description:
Explain standards and safety procedures used
regarding natural disasters.

95B889FC157F46F5B40F6F4F369AB553.description:
Mapping the history of natural hazards in a
region, combined with an understanding of
related geologic forces can help forecast the
locations and likelihoods of future events.

A52691263E7F418F9475F6F3BFAED32D.description:
Analyze and interpret data on
natural hazards to forecast future catastrophic
events and inform the development of
technologies to mitigate their effects.

2815DCEA32FC4E2D88F9A9D8387C6EA0.description:
Develop an argument based on evidence to
show how human activity is impacting the
quality and quantity of natural resources.

39270AD844164FACB736AFE7809155F1.description:
Create essential research questions related to
the distribution of natural resources.

C426FF50A8EF463FAFBB7A8B6609FF76.description:
These resources are distributed unevenly around
the planet as a result of past geologic processes.

8C993B9B07B847B2937A50B0FB668A47.description:
Minerals, fresh water, and biosphere resources
are limited, and many are not renewable or
replaceable over human lifetimes.

BC16E5B05EF6432CA8B6DE27B7073E98.description:
Humans depend on Earth’s land, ocean,
atmosphere, and biosphere for many different
resources.

153BBF053DB444179ACAC7E89FB450E2.description:
Construct a scientific explanation
based on evidence for how the uneven
distributions of Earth’s mineral, energy, and
groundwater resources are the result of past
and current geoscience processes.

901978EF703D46558596510B2C209581.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth and Human Activity

19BD7A93628D49BC9B7ECF3C77F94421.description:
Work collaboratively and respect the ideas,
roles, and abilities of others.

18DF58F4A0A24685B24771526F04D8E7.description:
Identify warm and cold currents on a
continental/world map.

A88C67C33711437A8FDFF9E4B6A321F8.description:
Use historical temperature data to
investigate factors that influence climate and
weather patterns and seasonal changes.

9DC85DF5C247489C8185954036E505CA.description: Use maps to explain regional climates.

14BBC53425C541688B0DEF023B0789D9.description:
Examine how geographic features affect
climate.

5FB8457734E6464B93E6CB407EF58C46.description:
Analyze how temperature, pressure and the
Coriolis Effect cause wind and water currents

DCA00BFAA588415086EF2299225A869A.description:
The ocean exerts a major influence on
weather and climate by absorbing energy
from the sun, releasing it over time, and
globally redistributing it through ocean
currents.

C50E2A32998E44F39335C1901948AE65.description:
These interactions vary with latitude,
altitude, and local and regional geography, all
of which can affect oceanic and atmospheric
flow patterns.

2D087F0D11284154B61FEC79DF7B935E.description:
Weather and climate are influenced by
interactions involving sunlight, the ocean, the
atmosphere, ice, landforms, and living things.

03A9651BFC194ABC92B1BA574B0F3C9F.description:
Variations in density due to variations in
temperature and salinity drive a global
pattern of interconnected ocean currents.

F9060AEC5F0E4A7FB0B2168A408A8AF3.description:
Develop and use a model to
describe how unequal heating and rotation
of the Earth cause patterns of atmospheric
and oceanic circulation that determine
regional climates.

ADD94C910B3A49CFBA078E1D9A83FD60.description:
Diagram how local lakes (Lake Michigan)
affect local weather.

2EB096F4255E469FA658197252F56FB8.description:
Demonstrate wind flow from high pressure
areas to low pressure areas; global
atmospheric movement influences local
weather.

D19FCC3C8E734B18B12FE3F2020EE333.description:
Explain how heat, moisture and air
movement determine weather.

05BFE3CBE842421CBBD22ADE29E01E6C.description:
Because these patterns are so complex,
weather can only be predicted
probabilistically.

10190781171546EEA44BFF0AA9B952B0.description:
The complex patterns of the changes and the
movement of water in the atmosphere,
determined by winds, landforms, and ocean
temperatures and currents, are major
determinants of local weather patterns.

B6A67EE4940D48FA8ADF821D2919B4CC.description:
Collect data to provide evidence
for how the motions and complex
interactions of air masses results in changes
in weather conditions.

C0B4AB9C0838436A9E4497EE3B47BA13.description:
Create an illustration to show the
composition and structure of the Earth’s
atmosphere.

B61D7BB4ADA24DE49046E458F8BFCFE6.description:
Demonstrate via model/diagram that the
Sun’s energy drives the water cycle and that
the water cycle is a continuous process of
recycling.

29E81CD9D0164B97B427F8F9E5140549.description:
Global movements of water and its changes
in form are propelled by sunlight and gravity

2E753C05EF8A4871A32C8BC733DAB0E0.description:
Water continually cycles among land, ocean,
and atmosphere via transpiration,
evaporation, condensation and
crystallization, and precipitation, as well as
downhill flows on land.

360FA61F47B04B2AB3DF7844130ADB97.description:
Develop a model to describe the
cycling of water through Earth’s systems
driven by energy from the sun and the force
of gravity.

2EA6BEDFD29849C0B60BBAC23303BE8A.description:
Design a model to demonstrate that Earth’s
crust is divided into plates that move in
response to mantle movement.

D34DEF2DBD724356841DDD172C699B41.description:
Distinguish between landforms that are
created through constructive and destructive
forces.

A4E235F5B4214647AEB558D4A5020220.description:
Construct an argument to show that the
fossils contained in the successive layers of
rock can be used to confirm the age, history
and changing life forms of the Earth.

899221220E2B4DECB79E32FF3224505C.description:
Maps of ancient land and water patterns,
based on investigations of rocks and fossils,
make clear how Earth’s plates have moved
great distances, collided, and spread apart.

67E6FFC5D5B646C680ED3C9345158EC0.description:
Tectonic processes continually generate new
ocean sea floor at ridges and destroy old sea
floor at trenches.

56A64B986FC24C0CA2767058BA88DBD2.description:
Analyze and interpret data on
the distribution of fossils and rocks,
continental shapes, and seafloor structures
to provide evidence of the past plate
motions.

D363CED4602A4E9687546341E0B297FF.description:
Compare and contrast how water, wind, and
ice cause weathering and erosion on Earth’s
surface.

2AB0E846358F4DE7ADDED568E2B1A896.description:
Identify and evaluate the impact of major
geologic events (earthquakes, volcanoes, or
other geoscience processes).

22EE61DC8C5E4777B631D84DA8D4424D.description:
Identify and evaluate the impact of local
geologic processes (landslides, coastal
erosion, glaciation changes).

A62833FD77CC46428414299945AEF7B8.description:
Explain how successive layers of sedimentary
rock are affected by folding, breaking and
uplifting layers.

C3B8D948AF3246C5BA6A381404FF647C.description:
Compare and contrast the interrelationships
involved in the process of the rock cycle.

1DC6681C5270494491E811C2CE1D1DE6.description:
Water’s movements—both on the land and
underground—cause weathering and
erosion, which change the land’s surface
features and create underground formations.

FD68DA6209D24F5EAE9D0789925CDC93.description:
These interactions have shaped Earth’s
history and will determine its future.

7065153A26754A59887264F4AF172A31.description:
The planet’s systems interact over scales that
range from microscopic to global in size, and
they operate over fractions of a second to
billions of years.

531DA02504624ED38DBF94D35767A595.description:
Construct an explanation based
on evidence for how geoscience processes
have changed Earth’s surface at varying time
and spatial scales.

C853BA625380413180F87BC11AEDAD60.description:
Describe the formation of soil including
texture, fertility and resistance to erosion.

611083B8F82448BD947B9A4F1473AF89.description:
Demonstrate the movement of energy
throughout the system of Earth’s layers.

EFC30472EE5947E5A54EF9D674935CBA.description:
Construct a model to show Earth is
comprised of layers including a core, mantle,
lithosphere, hydrosphere and atmosphere.

F25F415FED9C4CA49966847B41657D99.description:
The energy that flows and matter that cycles
produce chemical and physical changes in
Earth’s materials and living organisms.

89F4E00EA8664FD3B0873C5C2053011D.description:
This energy is derived from the sun and
Earth’s hot interior.

7B08E651D0AE4EC1A80E891B0BA0C49E.description:
All Earth processes are the result of energy
flowing and matter cycling within and among
the planet’s systems.

B1A5DA63408948BA88D79034ADFE0CEC.description:
Develop a model to describe the
cycling of Earth’s materials and the flow of
energy that drives this process.

4D665B11C7454366AEC81F8520E9C459.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth's Systems

B9FB0F58A1A34A5F8FF2E0DA4F12E5DC.description:
Work collaboratively and respect the ideas,
roles, and abilities of others.

CE2C0E4BB7944464B58DEDD787AA4CDF.description:
Discuss the theory of evolution in the context of
Catholic teaching about the origin of life.
(ES.1.4)

23056D34171B425A9EE063F330D38840.description:
Compare/describe life from the fossil record
with modern life forms and discuss Biblical
implications. (ES.1.4)

B7D28A8DA6E44B05A3497656A36E5A89.description:
Understand and appreciate that many different
people of varied cultures have made
contributions that benefit both
science and society. (ES.1.1)

070638D763AA45949CFD4F85390B8128.description:
Evaluate the ability of a space object to support
life.

FAA4829D576F42208E232A9813AB8054.description:
Compare and contrast characteristics of each
planet.

2473CCF5B1F9467C9DD0BD20FF9F73DF.description:
The geologic time scale interpreted from rock
strata provides a way to organize Earth’s
history. Analyses of rock strata and the fossil
record provide only relative dates, not an
absolute scale.

E34224A098834440A008252849CA4E02.description:
Construct a scientific explanation
based on evidence from rock strata for how the
geologic time scale is used to organize Earth’s
4.6-billion-year-old history.

1D4F2B6CA07240E4AAC2CAC97B3B0EAC.description:
Analyze data collected from various types of
telescopes and spacecraft.

B8FE803BFB5C46E58E5D3985F608DE8F.description:
Explain how telescopes are used to make
observations and collect data about the solar
system and the universe.

22D6D8DED80049BB9885CA6F0D39058F.description:
Develop a scale model to represent space
distances (planetary location).

70979C8CF0E54014805EFD92B303D155.description:
Celestial objects have features such as
planetary and orbital radii, atmosphere, and
surface features at different scales.

1497D8287F9A4BCAA023DF46E63325EB.description:
Data is collected from Earth-based, spacebased
telescopes, and from spacecraft.
Examples of data: drawings, photographs,
models, statistics.

40E2A9ED784E439D9D828E42ACE63674.description:
Realize light years and astronomical units are
used to measure distance in space.

7807E8520E1E4BD9892EED09D3772E9E.description:
Analyze and interpret data to
determine scale properties of objects in the solar
system.

4A6156FE5C664BD9B00F7839192E4948.description:
Understand how the force of gravity keeps the
planets and other bodies in orbit.

1E3307F552E64370AB4B8CDA1B1D4AFA.description:
Know that billions of galaxies exist in the
universe.

4DE0560CD1BA49B08099E0A674D0B556.description:
Understand how humans use technology to
explore space

0FB6EEB1B7E5400A86895314AE536D80.description:
The solar system appears to have formed from
a disk of dust and gas, drawn together by
gravity

F6E35F17F120488184BD738AB4E173B9.description:
The solar system consists of the sun and a
collection of objects, including planets, their
moons, and asteroids that are held in orbit
around the sun by its gravitational pull on
them.

A198C057721C43DDABD5DA9B4206DB80.description:
Earth and its solar system are part of the Milky
Way galaxy, which is one of many galaxies in
the universe

6447A37B94684B77B6640DB94178F752.description:
Develop and use a model to describe
the role of gravity in the motions within galaxies
and the solar system.

CA92D4A8D1E64516923B6BA97C63C560.description:
Summarize the accomplishments of a
contributing scientist (see vocab) to this science
domain.

1FE36B8ABBA2405C8E10B21BCC247D5E.description:
Draw a diagram or make a model to explain solar
and lunar eclipses.

4CDAAA4D8B5B4251809C23039E5EC7B2.description:
Describe how the tilt of the Earth determines
seasons and length of day.

68D404F993F84FBF9D82D349AF4A1C75.description:
Explain the orbital motion of objects in the solar
system.

A88CB34BF89A482CAD561DB3B692C96B.description:
The seasons are a result of that tilt and are
caused by the differential intensity of sunlight
on different areas of Earth across the year.

FCAF7840066845B1A046F78591847773.description:
Earth’s spin axis is fixed in direction over the
short-term but tilted relative to its orbit
around the sun.

B108AA2B5F5345C79460AFCEC27C584A.description:
This model of the solar system can explain
eclipses of the sun and the moon.

080B3C88BD524E6DA665026134DB7087.description:
Patterns of the apparent motion of the sun,
the moon, and stars in the sky can be
observed, described, predicted, and explained
with models.

BF7FDF878120458685D3103A45D4557C.description:
Develop and use a model of the
Earth-sun-moon system to describe the cyclic
patterns of lunar phases, eclipses of the sun and
moon, and seasons.

4DD896D93AEE4305A2B4329D4B39C2D2.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth's Place in the Universe

BFEC9532A7A14CE69CD05152E13DF62B.description:
Work collaboratively and respect the ideas, roles,
and abilities of others.

6C4D0EA4F7A94BD5A92F4F5648A85792.description:
Discuss the theory of evolution in the context of
Catholic teaching about the origin of life. (LS.4.6)

89E6C9EB22E54AAC836DE4F3BA83ECA5.description:
Explain how some of the changes on the earth are
contributing to changes in the balance of life and
affecting the survival or population growth of
certain species.

8E3DBC0E3B3F491E8A50169EAA35A77A.description: Know the history of the Theory of Evolution.

9171DF85CADA4E35B14626D99B59998C.description:
Recognize how organisms evolve, remembering
that God is the Author of all life.

C83A26D127444BAF8234AC38C9EB9848.description:
Traits that support successful survival and
reproduction in the new environment become
more common; those that do not become less
common. Thus, the distribution of traits in a
population changes.

CF013084FACF41F59483A499891E7CFD.description:
Adaptation by natural selection acting over
generations is one important process by which
species change over time in response to changes
in environmental conditions.

6A0403A777DA462F86DBA7FE7357D76F.description:
Use mathematical representations to
support explanations of how natural selection may
lead to increases and decreases of specific traits in
populations over time.

D16879AE839245DF86D6C4A79C6D37DF.description:
Project how current trends in human resource use
and population growth will influence the natural
environment, and show how current policies
affect those trends.

514AB854F23448B6B624DFFD1FB3418B.description:
One can choose desired parental traits
determined by genes, which are then passed
onto offspring.

53E7DC86D88A44FDAA6169554CB9E419.description:
In artificial selection, humans have the capacity
to influence certain characteristics of organisms
by selective breeding.

CEF6674EC33B4AEDAC7CAB7D107EA497.description:
Gather and synthesize information
about the technologies that have changed the way
humans influence the inheritance of desired traits
in organisms.

5F49E18C59A449EA9C92D469B98E4D8A.description:
Summarize the accomplishments of a contributing
scientist (see vocab) to this science domain.

AE3E77CA61FD4A15805A0DFEF0E2FD88.description:
Create data table and/or graph to convey data of
predator/prey within an environment.

1A2E3894B1884CD68EEFB0711201F1CC.description:
Simulate or create a visual to demonstrate the
process of natural selection (i.e. simulation game).

243E2608C9AA42FAB7F0FF256E942BF1.description:
Natural selection leads to the predominance of
certain traits in a population, and the
suppression of others.

B3A03610745D4AAD81E058D850F3135F.description:
Construct an explanation based on
evidence that describes how genetic variations of
traits in a population increase some individuals’
probability of surviving and reproducing in a specific
environment.

3AC6E648F0434BED98DFB15E646FC39F.description:
Describe the stages of development of a growing
embryo and fetus.

502D68E7BE3E41CC8485282ED64F760C.description:
Comparison of the embryological development of
different species also reveals similarities that
show relationships not evident in the fullyformed
anatomy.

46BB4EA8A5314464B05EDE64C6BC3640.description:
Analyze displays of pictorial data to
compare patterns of similarities in the
embryological development across multiple species
to identify relationships not evident in the fully
formed anatomy

D4A10C8E6141461791677EEEB45B0CB9.description:
Construct a model (branching tree) to
demonstrate relatedness.

BDE19DD3D2724E89B70F612B849A387E.description:
Compare and contrast skeletal systems of modern
species, as well as compare/contrast modern to
ancient.

E63DA074E40B40D389C16319200ED076.description:
Anatomical similarities and differences between
various organisms living today and between
them and organisms in the fossil record, enable
the reconstruction of evolutionary history and
the inference of lines of evolutionary descent.

fossil record.

In sexually reproducing organisms, each

contributing scientist (see vocab) to this
science domain.

Work collaboratively and respect the ideas,
roles, and abilities of others.

72EB1A16745B4821A889D75873E10E3D.description:
Apply an understanding of magnetic fields in an
experiment to magnetic fields in outer space.

DDF58D8AE62B4392A18653C5550B38EC.description:
Design an experiment using a magnet or a
compass to demonstrate magnetic fields.

4B093BF140094B0C8E7FC424095E174B.description:
Forces that act at a distance (electric, magnetic,
and gravitational) can be explained by fields
that extend through space and can be mapped
by their effect on a test object (a charged
object, or a ball, respectively).

25E6CD3239F34210B1688A3CBAB911D7.description:
Conduct an investigation and evaluate
the experimental design to provide evidence that
fields exist between objects exerting forces on
each other even though the objects are not in
contact.

CADF87AB655741A3BD9DDF3F3FD38290.description:
Construct and defend argument on gravitational
forces using data collected.

7DCB052CBCD94BE1899CC5484BF10E82.description:
Collect data (examples could include
simulations, digital tools, or charts) related to
strength of interactions, distance from the Sun,
or orbital periods of objects in the solar system.

B2034D6010DC4B01B2F2F21C7934D1BE.description:
There is a gravitational force between any two
masses, but it is very small except when one or
both of the objects have large mass—e.g., Earth
and the sun

E891C7EC9666470AA276CDF3F65C281F.description:
Construct and present arguments using
evidence to support the claim that gravitational
interactions are attractive and depend on the
masses of interacting objects.

66A40B036295442F8DFB57EA312D372F.description:
Develop a testable question and design an
experiment to determine factors that can
influence the strength of electromagnetic
forces.

93DC1C0FB86145699531BECE0A840B82.description:
Describe how magnetic field strength changes
with distance.

1361D0AE432A4C358E0A26F82DE48A97.description:
Electric and magnetic (electromagnetic) forces
can be attractive or repulsive, and their sizes
depend on the magnitudes of the charges,
currents, or magnetic strengths involved and on
the distances between the interacting objects.

0111FAA0EA9149FA85E6B7E7734DDE83.description:
Ask questions about data to determine
the factors that affect the strength of electric and
magnetic forces.

A0C5564C25F0452F87F8B4A4F69059CF.description:
Investigate the motion of objects and collect and
analyze to explain changes in motion in terms of
unbalanced forces.

C1E8CA5EDDEE486796666E0F6C949E14.description:
Articulate Newton’s Second Law of Motion and
provide examples.

6CDD2668A0AA4DEF9852B0E3FE52AB96.description:
All positions of objects and the directions of
forces and motions must be described in a
common choice of reference and specific units
of measurement (such as SI).

BC9227D8B9DC4181867955274131E83E.description:
For any given object, a larger force causes a
larger change in motion,

ED5EFA53ACE34DC6A0AB0CB287D645D5.description:
The greater the mass of the object, the greater
the force needed to achieve the same change in
motion.

79551055F93E42C09366272DD5099F31.description:
The motion of an object is determined by the
sum of the forces acting on it; if the total force
on the object is not zero, its motion will change

3C922010A97E4FC0B1FB0D64D30E0EAD.description:
Plan an investigation to provide
evidence that the change in an object’s motion
depends on the sum of the forces on the object
and the mass of the object.

FB400721671C47D9B211DE2AEFE05EF0.description:
Summarize the accomplishments of a
contributing scientist (see vocab) to this science
domain.

D169467E45C94925B08AE7B9CF4BFCAB.description:
Design a solution to a problem to demonstrate
the varying responses of two colliding objects,
such as:

A1B9F067183243F7AB469E359B473DE4.description:
Articulate Newton’s First and Third Law and
provide examples of each,

082E22A2DC9F4BB8ADD6FC2ED57D8B44.description:
For any pair of interacting objects, the force
exerted by the first object on the second object
is equal in strength to the force that the second
object exerts on the first, but in the opposite
direction (Newton’s third law).

7C85F4F090D54BF9B64B282163CF55FA.description:
Apply Newton’s Third Law to design a
solution to a problem involving the motion of two
colliding objects.

DB66B5D3BA584820A7E010342CAA783D.description: PHYSICAL SCIENCE: Motion and Stability: Forces and Interactions

F47C8EC750144A5399A0979547EFFD5D.description:
Demonstrate stewardship inspired by Catholic
values in the care of local and global environments.
(PS.1.3)

678B7D4A3CC940C3AABA6C21E3A5182B.description:
Work collaboratively and respect the ideas, roles,
and abilities of others.

6B0F189AE2DF4716847E1751F3B8104B.description:
Conduct an experiment and collect data to support
the law of conservation of thermal energy.

E53B433854474B28A68B52DB6A98B28E.description:
Some chemical reactions release energy,
others store energy.

466C2E5DE9A542BA8594979B0EEFF36C.description:
Undertake a design project to
construct, test, and modify a device that
either releases or absorbs thermal energy by
chemical processes.

BA8AC9E45B7E4A3EBD38CDC9E2327BDD.description:
Compare and contrast basic chemical reactions
(synthesis, decomposition, replacement).

AD7EDBC2D65C40658ECB1ADF6C357D33.description:
Illustrate that atoms are conserved in physical and
chemical processes.

D146020993F64172B29BD62B997D29FE.description:
The total number of each type of atom is
conserved, and thus the mass does not change.

56C688AA763D483793E64D3D4713F46F.description:
Develop and use a model to
describe how the total number of atoms does
not change in a chemical reaction and thus
mass is conserved.

25A8F5373D844ED7AD630E85F4D7055E.description:
Investigate fluid (air and/or liquid) pressure in
terms of speed and temperature.

B6FA4535D774495EA6C33D4D88DD7D95.description:
Recognize how a gain or loss of thermal energy
causes a physical change in state.

30211C464EB849E4842BA732F8498907.description:
Demonstrate how particle behavior changes as
thermal energy is added or removed.

35782EF61BEF4EC0B47A37A7BC6CCF8A.description:
Distinguish between the common use of the term
heat and the scientific application of that term.

20BE9653585D49C19F433C44E02D2492.description:
Compare and contrast the characteristics of
particles in a solid, liquid, and a gas.

35C83BFE254C42B5A51B4DF3FF410891.description:
The term “heat” as used in everyday language
refers both to thermal energy (the motion of
atoms or molecules within a substance) and
the transfer of that thermal energy from one
object to another. In science, heat is only used
for this second meaning; it refers to the energy
transferred due to the temperature difference
between two objects.

6B276B0E37734962B9CB23BC88675318.description:
The changes of state that occur with variations
in temperature or pressure can be described
and predicted using these models of matter.

D77D56C90ABC411A993A96B4098A8BCF.description:
In a liquid, the molecules are constantly in
contact with others; in a gas, they are widely
spaced except when they happen to collide. In
a solid, atoms are closely spaced and may
vibrate in position but do not change relative
locations.

D093CAA251DE44A3BDB16D97AF8EFFC1.description:
Gases and liquids are made of molecules or
inert atoms that are moving about relative to
each other.

3CE39E0B8052481BB15AE9600C628C29.description:
Develop a model that predicts
and describes changes in particle motion,
temperature, and state of a pure substance
when thermal energy is added or removed.

5D55F27E1B8549F2AFC17651BA4798D0.description:
Evaluate the sustainability of a product through its
life cycle.

D19CA3F09EF2425ABACD53F538471D20.description:
Trace the life cycle of a product made of synthetic
materials beginning with the natural resources.

935509198CEF41B8B5CBCF410406C2DC.description:
Substances react chemically in characteristic
ways.

59AE6C0451204D6FA654648D03BD97BF.description:
Gather and make sense of
information to describe that synthetic
materials come from natural resources and
impact society.

69F06C4D30FC459CB62567348F865AAF.description:
Observe, describe and identify changes in
properties based on chemical reactions. (burning
sugar or steel wool, vinegar and baking soda).

614045CA3D7D4935AE8BAF25015998B9.description:
In a chemical process, the atoms that make up
the original substances are regrouped into
different molecules, and these new substances
have different properties from those of the
reactants.

734D274793844461B1B1821366921EDA.description:
Each pure substance has characteristic physical
and chemical properties (for any bulk quantity
under given conditions) that can be used to
identify it

4060190CB6A44F389DC6BF29E907F900.description:
Analyze and interpret data on the
properties of substances before and after the
substances interact to determine if a
chemical reaction has occurred.

975AEF6C8152407BBEB4B75F50F3DF26.description:
Summarize the accomplishments of a contributing
scientist (see vocab) to this science domain.

2479D57CE027447E939EB38147FA0BE8.description: Compare and contrast covalent and ionic bonds

369FCF4E3D3947F9A6E1CE73BBB5CC53.description:
Model how molecules form based on the patterns
in the periodic table.

9EC1EBD9DABE433A82DA6F1003A5FD5C.description:
Differentiate how all matter is composed of atoms,
consisting of protons, neutrons, and electrons.

790DCADA6ED14A0C9938385D2594C291.description:
Describe organization of the Periodic Table
including how each element is represented.

4B3D558715D74F88A12993DC27D138A8.description:
Develop the historical perspective of the atomic
and molecular theory.

75C24654E2014B9B90D4CAACDA3819B5.description:
Solids may be formed from molecules, or they
may be extended structures with repeating
subunits (e.g., crystals).

5832B2DBDC634AE9AAFC2A9A54AA3906.description:
Atoms form molecules that range in size from
two to thousands of atoms.

DBE0125F5D2542968972F943E2D5AE0A.description:
Substances are made from different types of
atoms, which combine with one another in
various ways.

F12C4520496B4E7586BACD5160AE6F66.description:
Develop models to describe the
atomic composition of simple molecules and
extended structures.

1931603306B847368CE00DACF79FBB3C.description: PHYSICAL SCIENCE: Matter and Its Interactions
